
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `lspgpot` (List Package Global Package Output Table) yek dastoor dakheli dar FreeBSD ports system ast. In dastoor listi az hameye package-haye nasb shode va global package output table (PGPOT) ra namayesh midahad. Az aan baraye didan package-haye nasb shode va etela'at rabeteh ba package output table estefade mishavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `-v` --> 💬 Namayesh etela’at bishtar dar mored har package, mesle dependencies va file-haye nasb shode.
    🔹 `-q` --> 🤫 Faghat esm package-ha ra namayesh midahad, bedoone etela’at ezafi.
    🔹 `-o` --> 📤 Namayesh origin har package, yaani az koja download shode.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ lspgpot

    🔹 Namayesh listi az hameye package-haye nasb shode va PGPOT.

    $ lspgpot -v

    🔹 Namayesh etela’at bishtar dar mored har package.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ lspgpot | grep firefox

    🔹 Peyda kardan etela'at dar mored package `firefox`. Agar firefox nasb shode bashad, etela'ate aan namayesh dade mishavad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `lspgpot` (List Package Global Package Output Table) command is an internal command within the FreeBSD ports system. This command displays a list of all installed packages and the global package output table (PGPOT). It's used to view installed packages and information related to the package output table.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `-v` --> 💬 Show more verbose information about each package, such as dependencies and installed files.
    🔹 `-q` --> 🤫 Only display the package names, without any extra information.
    🔹 `-o` --> 📤 Display the origin of each package, meaning where it was downloaded from.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ lspgpot

    🔹 Display a list of all installed packages and the PGPOT.

    $ lspgpot -v

    🔹 Display more detailed information about each package.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ lspgpot | grep firefox

    🔹 Find information about the `firefox` package. If firefox is installed, its information will be displayed.

